# Weight

# Constraints
# number of passengers: 100


# What we need to get weight
# 1. Payload weight (passengers + luggage)
# 2. Zero fuel weight
    # 2.1. weight per unit volume of the waverider x volume of the waverider
#3. Fuel weight
    # 3.1. Amount of fuel required for the trip, given the distance and the engine efficiency
#4. Powerplant weight
    # 4.1. weight of the engine, given the required thrust and specific fuel consumption

# Assumptions
# weight of each passenger: 82.2 kg (Source: "Review of Standard Passenger Weights EASA.2021.C24")
# weight of luggage: 16 kg (Source: "Review of Standard Passenger Weights EASA.2021.C24")

# weight per unit volume of aircraft: ~62kg/m^3
# Weight of 737-200 is approx 54,249 kg empty, minus the propulsion weight of 8,177 kg, gives us 46,072 kg.
# The volume of the 737-200 is approximately 750 m^3, giving us a weight per unit volume of approximately 61.43 kg/m^3.
